49
00:02:52.120 --> 00:02:55.680
Let's look at how the field of AI developed in the last 20

50
00:02:55.700 --> 00:02:59.630
years. It all started with what we now call classical machine learning

51
00:02:59.660 --> 00:03:03.620
methods, where you train machine learning models to, for example, work with

52
00:03:03.740 --> 00:03:07.540
tabular data or with pre-extracted features from images to solve

53
00:03:07.640 --> 00:03:11.460
tasks such as prediction, prognostication, classification,

54
00:03:12.100 --> 00:03:12.840
et cetera.

55
00:03:13.920 --> 00:03:14.120
But,

56
00:03:15.160 --> 00:03:19.000
of course, as we all know, these methods were not sufficient for the

57
00:03:19.040 --> 00:03:22.340
complexity of data we face in cancer research,

58
00:03:22.490 --> 00:03:25.960
specifically image data, for example, histopathology

59
00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:29.800
images. So the field was completely changed in the 2010s when

60
00:03:29.860 --> 00:03:33.680
deep learning came along, and we were able to train deep learning models

61
00:03:33.780 --> 00:03:37.320
on large image datasets or other complex datasets

62
00:03:37.380 --> 00:03:40.900
for tasks such as classification, object

63
00:03:40.940 --> 00:03:43.480
segmentation, many others.

64
00:03:44.400 --> 00:03:48.320
In the 2020s, in the last couple of years, the field has

65
00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:51.200
been changed again by the advent of foundation models.

66
00:03:51.680 --> 00:03:55.360
These are big models that you train once with self-supervised learning

67
00:03:56.020 --> 00:03:59.700
on a large heterogeneous image cohort or

68
00:03:59.720 --> 00:04:03.700
dataset, and then you can use them and fine-tune

69
00:04:03.740 --> 00:04:07.500
them or apply them to additional

70
00:04:07.540 --> 00:04:11.360
downstream tasks. And typically, if you do this two-step approach, then you

71
00:04:11.400 --> 00:04:15.100
don't need as much data for the downstream tasks, and you can solve them

72
00:04:15.200 --> 00:04:19.060
much better. Another type of foundation models is, of course, large

73
00:04:19.101 --> 00:04:22.940
language models. These are just big foundation models that have been trained

74
00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:26.950
on natural language, so they can be used in natural language processing, but

75
00:04:26.960 --> 00:04:30.730
they have also obtained a generalist world

76
00:04:30.880 --> 00:04:34.740
knowledge and of course, are the basis for all the chatbots, ChatGPT, and

77
00:04:34.780 --> 00:04:36.260
everything that everybody's using.

78
00:04:36.960 --> 00:04:40.840
I think the most interesting part of these large language models is that

79
00:04:40.850 --> 00:04:44.740
they have enabled the technology of AI agents, where you

80
00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:48.560
take a large language model and you connect it to other tools so that it can

81
00:04:48.600 --> 00:04:52.560
solve complex tasks. Here, I'm going to show you

82
00:04:52.580 --> 00:04:56.440
a few examples how all of this comes together, how we can

83
00:04:56.540 --> 00:05:00.020
use deep learning to develop multimodal or unimodal

84
00:05:00.140 --> 00:05:03.860
biomarkers, and how we can then use AI agents

85
00:05:04.240 --> 00:05:06.280
to develop them much faster.

86
00:05:08.800 --> 00:05:11.420
First of all, let's speak about the biomarkers.

87
00:05:11.910 --> 00:05:15.720
And I want to just share this terminology that we have

88
00:05:15.760 --> 00:05:19.750
developed in our professional society, ESMO, European Society of Medical

89
00:05:19.800 --> 00:05:22.560
Oncology last year, and this has been published as a guideline.

90
00:05:23.700 --> 00:05:25.860
We've looked at the entire field of

91
00:05:26.980 --> 00:05:30.620
AI in cancer research and oncology, looked at the

92
00:05:30.720 --> 00:05:33.140
publications, looked at the products that are out there.

93
00:05:33.800 --> 00:05:37.120
And there's three classes of AI-based

94
00:05:37.160 --> 00:05:40.160
biomarkers, where AI is being used to derive

95
00:05:40.780 --> 00:05:44.620
properties of tumors that help us make better treatment decisions.

96
00:05:44.680 --> 00:05:48.560
Class A is using AI for biomarker quantification, and

97
00:05:48.600 --> 00:05:52.500
this is very simple because here what you're doing is you're just

98
00:05:52.700 --> 00:05:55.420
